urope (1815–1848), the 1930s in Europe, Sino-Soviet relations from 1949 to 1960, and the end of the Cold War. In each case he finds a clear relationship between the degree of ideological differences that divided state leaders and those leaders' perceptions of threat level (and so of appropriate foreign-policy choices). These relationships held in most cases, regardless of the nature of the ideologies in question, the offense-defense balance, and changes in the international distribution of power.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aGreat powers. 0aIdeology. 0aInternational relationsxDecision making. 0aWorld politics. 4aHistory. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Security (National & International).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781501732461?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501732461423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501732461/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles